{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472115"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:55:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:55:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1071"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1071"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.84,0.02,0.01,0.09,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1071"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114866"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1071"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1071"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96872"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"627"},{"type":"tags","id":"1115"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1401"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2320"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34513"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34912"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42214"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44039"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114866"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA five-month-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with her parent who is concerned about a mark on the child\u0027s abdomen. The lesion has been present since birth and has not changed in size or appearance. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her immunisations are up to date. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The lesion is seen (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance alone","Laser ablation","Cryotherapy","Oral propranolol","Excision"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with a congenital haemangioma (strawberry naevus), which is a common benign vascular birthmark. There are two subtypes: rapidly involuting congenital haemangioma (RICH) and non-involuting congenital haemangioma (NICH). The key distinguishing feature from infantile haemangiomas is that congenital haemangiomas are fully formed at birth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance alone\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management as these lesions are benign and typically grow proportionally with the child without causing complications. Parents should be advised that no intervention is necessary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaser ablation \u003C/strong\u003Ecould be considered as an alternative to surgical excision, but certainly would not be undertaken until the child is older.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECryotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for congenital haemangiomas as it may cause scarring and would not effectively treat the deeper vascular components of the lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral propranolol\u003C/strong\u003E is effective for infantile haemangiomas that develop in the first few weeks of life, but has no role in congenital haemangiomas as they do not have a proliferative phase after birth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcision\u003C/strong\u003E would only be considered for cosmetic reasons in selected cases, and even then, would typically be delayed until the child is older. The risks of surgery outweigh any potential benefits in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most congenital haemangiomas do not require intervention as they are benign and grow proportionally with the child.","Congenital haemangiomas are present at birth and differ from infantile haemangiomas which develop in the first few weeks of life.","Propranolol is not indicated for congenital haemangiomas but is used for infantile haemangiomas."],"references":["Smith CJF, Friedlander SF, Guma M, et al. Infantile Hemangiomas: An Updated Review on Risk Factors, Pathogenesis, and Treatment. Birth Defects Res 2017;109809-15. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28402073/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96872"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1071"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18673"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18673"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ca70281e-304e-4b53-9814-3f68c606d6a1.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ca70281e-304e-4b53-9814-3f68c606d6a1.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":414}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96872"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-21T11:38:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-21T11:41:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1071"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114866"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"cre